# The Loom experience

This document describes how a person works in Loom, from an empty directory to a published project: the command-line tool they reach for, the configuration they keep, the way they author across files and languages, how their looms run, and how the documentation is generated. It is the conceptual direction — written before the code, so the experience is designed rather than inherited piecemeal from the technical decisions underneath it.

_The present tense here states the target. Much of it is not yet built; this is the shape the implementation moves toward._

One idea runs through all of it. The literate document is the source, and everything else is derived from it — the files that land on disk, the configuration the tools read, the program that runs, the documentation site that ships. A person should never maintain a derived thing by hand.

## A Loom workspace

A workspace is the directory a person opens to work on a project. Loom marks one with a single committed file, `conf.loom`, at its root — the literate configuration, and the sign that says Loom lives here. Beside it sits `.loom/`, the directory Loom generates: the store of installed language services, the caches, and the compiled `config.yaml`. Git ignores the store and the caches, which Loom rebuilds on demand, while the compiled configuration is committed, so a checkout carries it.

The workspace, not the package, is the unit. One `conf.loom` governs the project: it names the languages the project uses, and Loom installs the service for each of them once, to serve the whole workspace. Its defaults — the primary language, the anchor delimiters — hold across the whole project; there is no per-package configuration. A monorepo composes its parts into separate packages through the book, where higher-order sinks place each part, not through a configuration of its own. The set of languages is fixed for the workspace too, because the editor runs a single language server over the project, and that one server has to know every language any part of it uses.

Loom looks for looms in a corpus directory, named `corpus` by default. An author who prefers another name — `prose`, say — sets it in `conf.loom`.

## The configuration is a loom

`config.loom` is itself a literate document. A framework that asks everyone else to write literately and then configures itself in plain JSON has broken its own premise, so Loom's configuration is a loom like any other: prose that explains each choice, beside the value it sets. It declares where the corpus lives, the primary language a section inherits when it names none, the languages the project has activated, the anchor delimiters, and the per-language settings. Where each file tangles is the book's to say, in its higher-order sinks, not the configuration's.

`conf.loom` is the single source of truth. The configuration files other tools expect — a `package.json` for a bundler, a `tsconfig.json` for the type-checker — Loom composes from it and hands to those tools in memory, rather than writing them into the project. The one thing that must live on disk is the language services themselves, under `.loom/`, because code that runs has to be a file. Configuration is virtual; only the installed packages are real.

## A loom composes many files, in many languages

A loom is not a file with its comments expanded. It is a narrative that composes a whole subsystem, and that subsystem is usually several files, often in several languages. One loom about a web feature may carry its markup in HTML, its behavior in TypeScript, its manifest in JSON, and its deployment in a shell script — each section in the language it belongs to, the prose explaining how they fit together. Tangle scatters the sections to the files they belong in; the reader keeps the single story.

This is the older and stronger form of literate programming. The weaker form — one literate file producing one source module, as in literate Haskell — keeps the prose but loses the composition, and with it most of the point. Loom takes the stronger form as its default: many files, many languages, one narrative. The order a person reads in is the order that explains best; the order code lands in is whatever the compiler needs. Knuth's WEB separated those two orders with named chunks; noweb made the chunk names themselves the output files and stayed language-agnostic; Loom inherits both and writes the file mapping into the document.

## Tangling — the author writes the path

If a loom composes many files, each section that produces one — a sink — names the file it writes, in braces in its heading: `## Behaviour {src/widget.ts}`. The path is the author's to write, and Loom infers no language's directory of its own. There is no built-in `src` for TypeScript, because where a language keeps its files is that language's convention, and a convention belongs in the path the author writes, not in a rule Loom imposes.

Loom resolves a sink against one place: the package root, the directory that holds the loom's `corpus/` folder. A project with `corpus/` at its workspace root tangles there, so `{widget.ts}` lands at `widget.ts` in the root. A package with its own `corpus/` tangles into that package. The one resolved root covers both the single project and the monorepo, with no path setting to configure.

Repeated path segments factor into a higher-order sink — a section whose specifier is a directory, `## The command line {packages/loom-cli/}`. Every sink it composes tangles under that prefix, so a leaf writes the short `{src/main.ts}` and lands at `packages/loom-cli/src/main.ts`. Nest one higher-order sink inside another and the prefixes accumulate down the tree. The prefix is the one construct that adds structure above a sink; a sink with none above it tangles straight to the package root.

The corpus shape and the output shape stay independent. A loom at `corpus/nice-app/nice-database/nice.loom` does not tangle to a mirror of that nesting — with no prefix above it, `{nice.ts}` lands at `nice.ts` in the package root. The narrative reads in whatever order suits a person, and the code lands where the paths and prefixes say. Neither shape is forced to follow the other.

## Activating a language

A project turns a language on with `loom add` — `loom add typescript`, `loom add python`. The command installs that language's service into the store under `.loom/` and records the language in `config.loom`. Its opposite, `loom remove`, takes both away. Nothing reaches the consumer's `package.json`, because a Loom project need not be a Node project at all.

Loom never installs behind the author's back. Opening a file in a language the project has not added does not silently run a package manager; the editor drops that language to syntax highlighting and offers the command that would add it. An install is something a person asks for.

## Running a loom

A loom runs without being tangled to disk first. The transform that turns a loom into code runs in memory — the way a development server compiles a component on the fly — so `loom run main.loom` executes the program with no generated files left in the tree. Writing files becomes a step for publishing, not a precondition for running.

How directly this works depends on the language, because composition runs on Node. For TypeScript and JavaScript the loader runs in the same process: it composes the loom and runs the result, with no separate build. For a language whose runtime is its own — Python, say — a small shim in that runtime loads composed source from a Loom daemon, so the program still runs from the loom with nothing on disk, at the cost of a process to bridge to. The pattern repeats per language: a thin loader in the language, a bridge back to Loom.

Loom itself keeps one exception. Because Loom is written in Loom, it cannot run its own corpus without a working Loom to run it, so the published command-line tool stays the trusted starting point that builds the next one. A consumer never meets this; their looms simply run.

## Building to publish

`loom build` is the step that produces artifacts to ship. It composes the corpus, writes the real files, and bundles them for distribution — and only here does Loom write out the configuration files it kept virtual, because the registry and the bundler that receive the package read them from disk. Development runs from looms; publishing emits the conventional thing the outside world expects.

## Weaving the documentation

Tangle produces the code; weave produces the documentation. `loom weave` builds a static website from the corpus — the prose and the code together, the sections navigable, an anchor a link to the section it names. It is the half of literate programming that faces the reader: where Knuth's weave typeset a program as a book, Loom's weave publishes the corpus as a documentation site. The prose that tangle discards is, here, the product.

## The command surface

The commands are few, and each one names the thing it does.

- `loom init` sets up a workspace — it writes `config.loom` and `.loom/`, and asks for nothing it can reasonably default.
- `loom add <language>` and `loom remove <language>` turn a language on and off.
- `loom status` shows what is active, what is installed, and where the store is.
- `loom run <file>` runs a loom in memory.
- `loom build` emits and bundles for publishing.
- `loom weave` generates the documentation website.
- `loom tangle <path>` writes composed files to disk, for a build that wants that step on its own.
- `loom lsp` starts the language server the editor talks to; a person rarely types it.

Underneath the list is a standard the commands hold to. Each verb names its own action, so the command line reads as the thing it performs. The common path is short — `init`, then `add` — and asks for nothing a sensible default can supply. The committed configuration is visible and the generated state is disposable, so a person can always read the truth and throw the rest away. Every command that turns something on has the command that turns it off. And nothing that runs code happens by surprise: an install is asked for, never triggered by opening a file.
